    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>I don't anyone can seriously claim that in Greece there wasn't a need for <em>some</em> level of budget cuts. The depth and pace of those cuts, however, were ill-advised by the troika.</p>
<p>Austerity bills slashed public sector pay by over 1/3 while private sector wages (minimum wage) were decreased by over 20%.</p>
<p>Because of the austerity, 1 in three Greeks lives at or below the poverty level. That's insane.</p>
<p>The problem with how the troika handled Greece was that their strategy was initially premised on containment, not stimulus. The first bailouts didn't go towards stimulating Greece's economy. Billions of euros were spent simply to shore up the European banking system that had exposure to Greek debt. In fact, The New York Times reported that bailout funds were wired from European banks to an escrow account in Athens that the Greek government couldn't touch and then wired back to European banks days later for debt service.</p>
<p>So yes, while Greece didn't have the choice of taking some level of austerity off the table, it certainly didn't have to acquiesce so quickly to the depth of austerity demanded by the troika or the terms which largely focused on debt service for too long to the exclusion of a real stimulus program that would have helped strengthen Greece's economy and in turn, its negotiating position on bonds, debt, etc.<br /></p>

  </div>
