  <div class="ct">
  
<p>Think a moment. &nbsp;For the last two centuries, the American economy has been a growth machine. &nbsp;The only thing necessary to assure growth, has been for national policies not to be too damned stupid for too long. &nbsp;The world economy was expanding, technology was increasing at ever-more-rapid pace, and therefore while fiscal tight-fistedness could slow that trend down, it wouldn't reverse it, while economic investment paid secure dividends.</p>
<p>But this isn't your grandmother's world anymore. &nbsp;Infinite growth simply is not possible for anything in a finite universe, even less so on a small planet that lacks effective transport technology to escape the gravity well, the magnetic shield, and the solar system. &nbsp;The limits to economic growth and human population have been exceeded already; we can't continue at the pace we've been going, let alone expand. &nbsp;Our waste products already threaten to upset the long-term climate balance to which our biology is adapted.</p>
<p>In this context, NEW wealth isn't going to be created (no growth). &nbsp;Economics becomes a zero sum game; nobody can increase their portion of the pie without taking it from someone else. &nbsp;It's quite possible that the wealthy who own and operate the economic system for their own survival and profit have moved into cannibalistic mode, where they are deliberately scavenging whatever scraps of wealth they can from wherever and whoever has them, intent on draining everything they can into their own coffers. &nbsp;There's simply no <em>point</em> (from their position) in trying to maintain the overall health of the system; at this time that would cost them without returning any profits. &nbsp;And of course the governments and national banks continue to dance to their tune.</p>

