    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<blockquote>You would think that the U.S., looking across the Atlantic to a European wasteland filled with record high employment rates, collapsing middle classes, and massive poverty, would think twice before acting on the same type of austerity here at home.</blockquote>
The US <em>has already</em> destroyed its middle class, forced millions into poverty, and offers up less than living wage jobs with no benefits or protections to its workers. The GOP has been wanting to roll back the little safety net Americans do enjoy for decades. They've been wanting to drown government in a bathtub for how long now?
<p>Both the Democrats and the Republicans have presided over the greatest shift in wealth in American history. <em>BOTH</em> of them have. They both answer to the same paymaster while dangling social issues (that should have been decided decades ago) in front of the American people to get us to fight one another while robbing us blind.</p>
<p>If the wealth chasm were imaginary, I'm certain that the US would be pushing austerity at home. The sad thing is, they don't need to anymore. They already got your money, now they want the European middle classes cash as well.</p>
<p>If these global plutocrats get their way, the US will sign a free trade agreement with the EU. Once that happens, we (Europeans) can say good-bye to social democracy. The plutocrats hate the social democracies in Europe. The weak ones they can snuff out with austerity while the stronger ones will be laid low by "competition" with American workers whose employers and government couldn't care less about them.</p>

